04003nam a22005535i 9780822391692DE-B159720201028084219.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201028t20102010ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223916927 a10.1515/97808223916922doi  a(DE-B1597)552801  a(OCoLC)1136294474  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aDS510.7b.C44 2010 7aHIS0030002bisacsh04a950.0722221 aChen, Kuan-Hsing, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAsia as Method :bToward Deimperialization /cKuan-Hsing Chen. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2010] 4cÂ©2010  a1 online resource (342 p.) :b1 table  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tIntroduction Globalization and Deimperialization -- tChapter 1 The Imperialist Eye -- tChapter 2 Decolonization -- tChapter 3 De-Cold War -- tChapter 4 Deimperialization -- tChapter 5 Asia as Method -- tEpilogue The Imperial Order of Things, or Notes on Han Chinese Racism -- tNotes -- tSpecial Terms -- tBibliography -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aCentering his analysis in the dynamic forces of modern East Asian history, Kuan-Hsing Chen recasts cultural studies as a politically urgent global endeavor. He argues that the intellectual and subjective work of decolonization begun across East Asia after the Second World War was stalled by the cold war. At the same time, the work of deimperialization became impossible to imagine in imperial centers such as Japan and the United States. Chen contends that it is now necessary to resume those tasks, and that decolonization, deimperialization, and an intellectual undoing of the cold war must proceed simultaneously. Combining postcolonial studies, globalization studies, and the emerging field of "Asian studies in Asia," he insists that those on both sides of the imperial divide must assess the conduct, motives, and consequences of imperial histories.Chen is one of the most important intellectuals working in East Asia today; his writing has been influential in Taiwan, South Korea, Hong Kong, Japan, Singapore, and mainland China for the past fifteen years. As a founding member of the Inter-Asia Cultural Studies Society and its journal, he has helped to initiate change in the dynamics and intellectual orientation of the region, building a network that has facilitated inter-Asian connections. Asia as Method encapsulates Chen's vision and activities within the increasingly "inter-referencing" East Asian intellectual community and charts necessary new directions for cultural studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Okt 2020) 0aCulturexStudy and teachingzEast Asia. 0aGlobalizationzEast Asia. 0aPostcolonialismzEast Asia. 7aHISTORY / Asia / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822391692zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822391692423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822391692.jpg  a978-3-11-071183-7  DUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles